# Databases
## What is a database in general?
If you visit sites like Twitter, LinkedIn and GitHub, you know that you need an account in order to use the features of the site. You need an account to tweet things, connect with other people, or store your projects in a remote server. In order to keep track of the activities of your account and make a reference, they would need to have your account information stored somewhere (and I think you already know the answer).

Pretty much the concept of using a database is not limited to online sites and services. Every organization from educational institutions to governments utilize a database in order to keep tabs on their important data and any data that might be useful as reference. Your student data (the year, the section/block, their unpaid and paid fees, etc), for example, is kept on a database to keep track between colleges and their students. Another example could be your bank account being securely stored (hopefully) in databases so that the bank can keep track of your account.

<img style="display: block;margin: 0 auto;" src="data:image/png;base64,">

With that being said, when we talk about databases, we mostly think about a collection of data stored somewhere.

## What is a database in programming?
We can stop the introduction there but let's discuss databases with the context closer to programming.

The output of computer programs in it of itself are mostly stateless. Once our program has made an output and exited, it'll be out from the system as if the program never ran before. It is up to you on how to make the data persistent. On usual cases, we just log the output into files that is stored on a persistent storage space like the hard disk drives (HDD) or solid state drives (SSD) or whatever data storage device available.

However, there are also cases wherein we need to refer to our output files and update the needed data. We could just do it but without planning and preparation, it'll most likely be a mess. In order to make the process of navigating through the data much smoother, we need to organize our data and giving a standard structure.

**That is what a database at its core, an organized collection of data.** 

## Database management systems
Now, if you're familiar with web programming, you most likely encountered the words SQL, MongoDB, MySQL, and SQLite. These are not a form or a type of database but rather they are software that lets you operate data on the database. Otherwise, known as a database management system, often referred to as DBMS.

Programmers identify DBMSs according to which data model they support. Examples of such DBMSs are [MySQL](https://www.mysql.com/), [MongoDB](https://mongodb.com/), and [Redis](https://redis.io/) which support relational databases, document-oriented databases, and key-value store databases, respectively.

## Different database model
Here are the common modern data model on how to navigate around the data:

- Relational database &mdash; composed of a series of tables made up of columns and rows (i.e. [PostgreSQL](https://www.postgresql.org/))
- Graph database &mdash; represents its data in a graph and it's mostly suitable to store information involved with networks
- Document-oriented database &mdash; composed of collections of documents as an entry point of the data (i.e. [MongoDB](https://mongodb.com/))
- Key-value database &mdash; composed of an associative array, also known as a dictionary or an object (i.e. [Redis](https://redis.io))
- Wide-column database &mdash; its data are stored in a big column and can be seen as a two-dimensional key-value store (i.e. [HBase](https://hbase.apache.org/))
- Flat file database &mdash; it is composed of one table where all of the data are stored 

Different database management systems often utilize and support one data model which implies that you have to choose your database system and know the pros and cons of each DBMS. We can narrow our choices into (mostly) two: SQL-based DBMS and NoSQL-based DBMS but first let's go with a bit of exploration with the common concepts of databases and database management systems.

## Some database concepts
### Records
**A *record* is basically the entry points of individual data inside of the database.** For example, in a phonebook database, we have a database composed of recipients with their names and phone numbers. In this case, we have a phonebook database composed of records of individual recipients.

Another example could be easily seen in a spreadsheet. Say that you have a spreadsheet of members in your local programming club. The records of the spreadsheet is the individual rows that represents one of the users.

### Attributes
**An *attribute* is one of the characteristic(s) in each record.** Going back to the phonebook database example, we have a database composed of records of recipients and we already established that each record is further composed of their names and phone numbers. The attributes of the recipient records here are the name and the phone number.

As for the spreadsheet example, the attributes is the spreadsheet headers which is represented in a column. Say that each member in the spreadsheet has their name, alias, email address, Discord ID, and the number of times they attended in the meetup. Those are the attributes for each record.

### Fields
**A *field* is the individual value of each record.** Again with the phonebook database, we described a database composed of recipient records with each record holds a value for a name and a phone number. The actual value of the name and the phone number is the field, specifically the fields of a particular record.

For the spreadsheet example, the value of the name, email address, Discord ID, and the number of times they attended in a meetup is the field. In other words, it is simply the individual cell. Also take note that a field may be empty (or null, in programming terms) though it is not possible for a record to have all of its fields empty. A member of your club may not have an available Discord ID but it is certainly not possible for them to not have a name.

Let's make the local programming club member spreadsheet example to be real.

| Name | Alias | Email Address | Discord ID | # of Attendance
| --- | --- | --- | --- | --- |
| John Dodoe | john_dodoe | johndodoe@notrealdomain.com | john_dodoe#6531 | 3
| Nat Aboi | not_a_boi | nataboi@troll.com | notaboi#0001 | 1
| Ren Po | renpooooooooo | renpo@note.com | renpooooooo#0284 | 1
| Jarvis Johnjohn | JJ | jarvisjohnjohn@itsnotgmail.com | jj#1234 | 2
| Nathalia True | nuttela_is_true | nathaliatrue@false.com | null | 2
| Javid De Jesus | JDJ | javiddejesus@tmail.com | null | 1

If we want to describe this spreadsheet, we would describe it with the following properties:

- it's a spreadsheet of the members in the local programming club
- currently, the local programming club has 6 members
- each member of the local programming club must have their name and email address listed
- each of the members listed in the spreadsheet has their details of the name, alias, email address, Discord ID, and the number of times they attended in meetups

### Primary keys
In order to make our items in the spreadsheet to be identifiable, we need to have a way to have one of their attributes in each record to contain truly unique values. That is the main purpose for primary keys and that is what primary keys are. **They are simply unique values to make each record identifiable.**

This is one of the most important steps when populating a database. After all, you will not only create new values over time. You also have to read, update, and delete them, if necessary. Most likely in those operations, you have to rely with the unique key in order to search through the database.

Let's take the same spreadsheet with the local programming club members. Let's inspect each attributes and see if one of them can be the primary key.

The name obviously cannot be the primary key. Even though the chances are very low, we cannot guarantee that their names will be unique. Aliases also cannot be our primary key as we cannot guarantee it is unique as people themselves can choose their aliases. Email addresses are a tricky thing but we cannot consider it either. Yes, it can be unique but it is not required, meaning members can lack the field for email address and it can be very tricky to search through for them. The same principle applies to the Discord ID. The number of times they attended the meetups cannot be the primary key for obvious reasons.

So how do we solve this case? Well, we can simply create the primary keys for ourselves. If you've ever noticed that in certain environments such as schools, organizations, and memberships, they tend to use primary keys to easily identify you and its members. For example, schools usually attach their students with ID to easily search through their student database. We also have certain government services wherein they require an ID of some kind like insurances, benefits, and pension. 

For our case with the spreadsheet, we will simply add a membership ID attribute to all of them. The membership ID is simply a number but unlike names, aliases, and the attendance, it does not rely on anything except for the order when they joined the membership so at least we have a guarantee for the ID to be unique.

| Membership ID | Name | Alias | Email Address | Discord ID | # of Attendance
| --- | --- | --- | --- | --- | --- |
| 1 | John Dodoe | john_dodoe | johndodoe@notrealdomain.com | john_dodoe#6531 | 3
| 2 | Nat Aboi | not_a_boi | nataboi@troll.com | notaboi#0001 | 1
| 3 | Ren Po | renpooooooooo | renpo@note.com | renpooooooo#0284 | 1
| 4 | Jarvis Johnjohn | JJ | jarvisjohnjohn@itsnotgmail.com | jj#1234 | 2
| 5 | Nathalia True | nuttela_is_true | nathaliatrue@false.com | null | 2
| 6 | Javid De Jesus | JDJ | javiddejesus@tmail.com | null | 1

Instead of referring to the names, aliases, or email addresses where they could be the same (or empty) for someone else, we can just refer to them by the membership ID we assigned for them.

### Transactions
In banks, whenever you want to withdraw and deposit some amount of money, they would call it as a transaction to your account. In case that a bank transaction has failed because of system errors, the transaction will be cancelled. When you try to withdraw $100 from your account that has a balance of $2000 and there was a system fail while doing it, the transaction is cancelled and your account balance is still $2000 as if that transaction was never opened in the first place.

That's quite similar to *how* a database transaction works but *what* is a database transaction.

Similar to bank transactions, a database transaction is a logical unit of instructions for interacting with the database. In order to write or read to a database, you have to open a transaction first. Any possible actions such as updating, deleting, and querying requires a transaction to be opened first but why?

Simply put, there would be serious consequences when we don't have a mechanism for grouping a bunch of actions. Going back to the bank transactions example of withdrawing $100 from your account balance of $2000 &ndash; even if you didn't receive your $100, the transaction-less system would recognize it in case the withdrawal process has been successful. Thus, you have $1900 in your account balance. You see how it would be bad? 

Most DBMS already takes care of how a transaction should be opened or closed but it doesn't mean we can entirely leave out those details since errors are bound to happen. 

### Schema
A database schema is the skeleton of the data. **It describes the relationship between each field and the procedures of how the data should be stored and what type of data it contains.** It is basically the blueprint of the database, complete with details of its interiors and how it should be built.

We'll still take the local programming club members spreadsheet example from before to see how a schema really is.

| Membership ID | Name | Alias | Email Address | Discord ID | # of Attendance
| --- | --- | --- | --- | --- | --- |
| 1 | John Dodoe | john_dodoe | johndodoe@notrealdomain.com | john_dodoe#6531 | 3
| 2 | Nat Aboi | not_a_boi | nataboi@troll.com | notaboi#0001 | 1
| 3 | Ren Po | renpooooooooo | renpo@note.com | renpooooooo#0284 | 1
| 4 | Jarvis Johnjohn | JJ | jarvisjohnjohn@itsnotgmail.com | jj#1234 | 2
| 5 | Nathalia True | nuttela_is_true | nathaliatrue@false.com | null | 2
| 6 | Javid De Jesus | JDJ | javiddejesus@tmail.com | null | 1

In this case, we have one database which contains the record for the members and the records already have its attributes set. Now we just need to set some additional details for them. Let's say that in our database, the alias should only contain alphanumeric characters. Another should be that the membership ID and the number of attendance should only be an integer. 

## SQL and NoSQL
OK! Now that we have talked a few concepts of the databases and DBMS, let's go with SQL and NoSQL, two of the most common keywords when it comes to databases.

### SQL
SQL, stands for *Structured Query Language*, is a standardized language for describing the syntax of interacting with relational databases. As already mentioned, relational databases are basically databases that uses tables composed of rows and columns. Take note that not all relational DBMS (or RDBMS) use SQL as their language but most of them (or the famous ones) do. We have [PostgreSQL](https://postgresql.org/), [MySQL](https://www.mysql.com/), [SQLite](https://sqlite.org/), [Microsoft SQL Server](https://www.microsoft.com/en-us/sql-server), and even [Microsoft Access](https://office.microsoft.com/access) and its open source counterpart, [LibreOffice Base](https://www.libreoffice.org/discover/base/) (though you have to use some kind of method to do it).

There are several advantages and disadvantages of using SQL-based RDBMS. 

First, its pros:

- **They have a standard language for database interaction** &mdash; No suprise, it's SQL. Having it standardized means that most of them uses the same syntax and can get you easily use one SQL-based RDBMS over another once you get used to writing SQL syntax. Though, keep in mind that not all of them are the same and some of them have a custom syntax (or additional functions) of their own. Just refer to the their respective documentations and check their proprietary syntax and you'll be fine.
- **ACID-compliant** &mdash; [ACID](https://www.geeksforgeeks.org/acid-properties-in-dbms/) is a set of properties that describes how database transactions should be in order to guarantee data survival even in cases of system failures and in order to make the database consistent when multiple operations are being exectued at a single time. Basically, this provides a mechanism for database transactions that should be able to interact with the database with correctness. 
- **Strong mathematical basis** &mdash; The origin of relational databases is quite mathematical in nature. You could also apply concepts from relational algebra, relational calculus, and mathematical logic in order to fully express the operations and bridge mathematics along with it.
- **Features declarative syntax** &mdash; Being declarative in nature means that you can easily get what the operation is about with a glance. Take the following SQL statement for an example: `SELECT * FROM Members WHERE membership_id > 5`. Even if you've never seen a SQL statement before, you can get an idea of the syntax indicates and it pretty much reads like an English statement, too.

Basically, one of the strongest points of SQL-based DBMS is its flexibility when it comes to using similar DBMS and its readability. Since SQL-based DBMS uses, well, SQL as their language, you'll be using pretty much only one type of syntax even with all of their exclusive syntax extensions. Also, SQL syntax really looks like an English sentence which you (and others) have an easier time reading it.

However, there are some tradeoff to bear in mind when considering to use SQL-based DBMS:

- **Requires a predefined schema and all data must follow the schema** &mdash; When starting with a SQL-based DBMS, you can't just start a session and use it immediately. Using a SQL-based DBMS requires you to have a predefined schema and all of the data must follow that schema. It also implies that if you want to change a part of the structure, you would have to disrupt your system for a bit in order to apply the changes. Overall, it would be a cumbersome process and if you want to reduce the chances of that scenario to ever happen, you would need some amount of preparation to model your data.
- **Usually, scalling are done vertically** &mdash; Considering scalability, in order to increase load within the SQL-based DBMS, you would have to increase the hardware specifications of the machine. This is what the IT industry calls *vertical scaling*. Since vertical scaling depends on the highest available hardware resources, it could also mean that the program could hit a block and would need a system upgrade. Since changing certain hardware stuff such as RAM and CPU requires the computer to be offline for slightly obvious reasons (electrical hazards, potential system corruption, among many others), it would mean that your server would have to be put down momentarily for maintenance/system upgrade. Though, there's still some SQL-based databases that support horizontal sharding.

### NoSQL
With all of that said and done, let's see what NoSQL-based DBMS offers but let's take a look on what is NoSQL.

NoSQL, stands for *Not Only SQL*, is basically an alternative to SQL. With SQL revolving around relational databases, NoSQL obviously revolves around non-relational databases. This is where databases of other data models are to be found: key-value stores, graph databases, document-oriented databases, wide column databases, and much more.

The notion of NoSQL was developed simply as an alternative for SQL, not a full-on replacement. Also, it is mostly catered for web-based applications, specifically the scaling which is one of its main features. 

Being a class of databases that classifies that databases that are not relational databases, it surely does have numerous examples. According to [this site](http://nosql-database.org/), it has at least more than 225 NoSQL-based DBMS. A few popular examples include:
 
- [MongoDB](https://www.mongodb.org/) &mdash; A document-oriented DBMS
- [Cassandra](https://cassandra.apache.org/) &mdash; A wide column store/database
- [Elastic](https://www.elasticsearch.org/) &mdash; Another one of the popular document-oriented DBMS, similar to MongoDB
- [CouchDB](http://couchdb.apache.org/) &mdash; Another document store

So what are their advantages to SQL-based DBMS? Well:
- **Dynamic schema** &mdash; In other words, they don't need any predefined schema. You can get started with data modelling and interacting with the database management system. This also eliminates the painstaking process of updating the schema of your data if you want to change it.
- **Horizontally scaling** &mdash; As previously discussed, there are generally two types of scaling: vertical scaling and horizontal scaling. SQL-based DBMS generally needs to be scaled vertically if you want to have your program handle more resources which means you have to upgrade the hardware resources of your machine. Meanwhile, since NoSQL databases are generally made for modern web application scaling, you generally just need to scale horizontally. Meaning you just have to add more machines rather than upgrade the hardware of one machine.
- **Various data models** &mdash; Since the category includes everything else that is not SQL-based, of course it's going to have a variety of data models to choose from. It just depends on you on how to store the data with the data model that you chose to interact with.
- **CAP theorem-compliant** &mdash; With SQL-based DBMS choosing consistency with the principles from [ACID](https://www.geeksforgeeks.org/acid-properties-in-dbms/), NoSQL databases choose to go with availability over consistency. However, it does presents some problems especially when errors have occured. Overall, this can be a double-edged sword type of situation.

As said previously before, one of the biggest marketing points of NoSQL databases is its scalability. Unlike SQL databases which presents some problems when scaling either horizontally or vertically, NoSQL databases are simple enough that you can just go with scaling horizontally. Furthermore, usually NoSQL databases are easier to get started with if you want to quickly create data so prototyping can be one of the strong points with these databases.

Now let's look at its disadvantages:
- **Does not have standardized language** &mdash; NoSQL doesn't have a standard language to unite all NoSQL databases together (I guess because they have different data models). It also implies about the syntax of the NoSQL database which will be different from one another so you'll have to read the documentations well.
- **Consistency error-prone** &mdash; Dynamic schemas can lead to manual error problems wherein data may go unstructured and messy, overall. Since it doesn't particularly stop you from having your data records to be consistent with their attributes (most of the time), that's where data consistency problems may rise.
- **Not much data integrity options** &mdash; Dynamic schemas (or rather, the absence of schema) also leads to a lack (or inadequate) options when it comes to data integrity for NoSQL databases. Since data can be added anywhere at any time, there won't be any checking to make sure that references or other related data are around unless the DBMS offers an option or you implemented one.
- **Not suitable for complex queries** &mdash; Or at least it'll be messy. Unlike SQL-based DBMS which features joining of queries to make more complex queries, NoSQL databases doesn't usually have the option of doing so.

With the discussions of both types said and done, let's get into one of the most important point of choosing a database management system.

### When to use SQL or NoSQL?
With endless debates, articles, and discussions floating in the web, you expect to find a definite answer. In reality though, it depends on you (and your team/company, if you're working with one) but let's get ideal with the answers.

Both are a generalized type of database system and both offer a different approach to store your data. One offers an out-of-the-box way to strictly enforce creation and updating of data to be as consistent as possible and the other offers an easy way to get started with storing your data but at the cost of consistency. One offers a great standardized language that will be easier to fit in between different database software and the other offers ease of scaling for your web programs, as originally intended. 

Though there are additional tools from each DBMS that is going to extend the functionalities of each DBMS, it's way easier in the long run to study a bit on the selection of tools that you have and play prototyping with them before deciding what DBMS is the main winner. 

Heck, you could even combine different DBMS to be used in one system. Say that you can use a SQL-based DBMS for low-value data but high in quantity like log entries then use a NoSQL database for highly valuable data like user data. That's just one way of using them.
